Now let me compile the full audit. Here are the findings:

---

## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `SerializerTests.cs`

**Summary: 5 Critical · 0 High · 2 Medium · 1 Low**

This suite is dominated by **self-referential / tautological assertions**. Six of eight tests assert `output == input` by choosing inputs that make the operation under test a no-op. These tests inflate coverage while proving almost nothing.

---

### 🔴 Critical — False Confidence

#### 1. `UpperCase_ToUpper_Works` (line 72–77) — Self-referential assertion

The input `"HELLO"` is already uppercase, so `.ToUpper()` returns it unchanged. The test asserts `input == result` — a tautology. Additionally, this tests `string.ToUpper()` (BCL), not any production code.

```csharp
// BEFORE — always passes, even if ToUpper were deleted
var input = "HELLO";
var result = input.ToUpper();
Assert.AreEqual(input, result);

// FIX — test actual transformation; or delete entirely (don't test the BCL)
var input = "hello";
var result = input.ToUpper();
Assert.AreEqual("HELLO", result);
```

#### 2. `NormalizeName_AlreadyNormalized_NoChange` (line 37–42) — Self-referential assertion

`"alice"` is already trimmed and lowercase. `Normalize` does `Trim().ToLowerInvariant()`, so the output equals the input. If `Normalize` were a no-op (`return name;`), this test still passes.

```csharp
// BEFORE — input is already normalized, so transform is invisible
var name = "alice";
var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize(name);
Assert.AreEqual(name, result);

// FIX — use input that requires transformation
var name = "  ALICE  ";
var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize(name);
Assert.AreEqual("alice", result);
```

#### 3. `GetDisplayName_ReturnsFormattedName` (line 56–61) — Self-referential assertion

Production code: `GetDisplayName() => Name;` — it returns the property unchanged. The test asserts `user.Name == display`, which is asserting the implementation, not the intended behavior. The method name implies formatting, but the test would pass with any identity implementation.

```csharp
// BEFORE — asserts output == input property
var display = user.GetDisplayName();
Assert.AreEqual(user.Name, display);

// FIX — assert against a literal expected value that reflects intended behavior
// (if the method SHOULD format, fix the method too)
var user = new UserDto { Name = "Alice", Age = 30 };
var display = user.GetDisplayName();
Assert.AreEqual("Alice (30)", display);  // assert the INTENDED format
```

#### 4. `MapToDto_MapBack_RoundTrip` (line 45–53) — Round-trip masks data loss

This is the most dangerous test. The production `Mapper` **loses data**:
- `ToDto`: drops `Id`, hardcodes `Age = 0`
- `ToEntity`: hardcodes `Id = 0`, drops `Email`

The round-trip asserts `entity.Id == backToEntity.Id` (1 vs 0) and `entity.Email == backToEntity.Email` ("a@b.com" vs ""), so **this test should actually fail**. If the previous team reported it as passing, either the mapper was different or the test was never run. Either way, the round-trip pattern here hides that the mapping is lossy.

```csharp
// FIX — test the forward mapping directly with literal expected values
[TestMethod]
public void ToDto_MapsFullNameToName()
{
    var entity = new UserEntity { Id = 1, FullName = "Alice Smith", Email = "a@b.com" };
    var dto = Mapper.ToDto(entity);
    Assert.AreEqual("Alice Smith", dto.Name);
    // NOTE: Age is hardcoded to 0 — is this intentional? Add assertion or fix mapper.
}

[TestMethod]
public void ToEntity_MapsDtoNameToFullName()
{
    var dto = new UserDto { Name = "Alice Smith", Age = 30 };
    var entity = Mapper.ToEntity(dto);
    Assert.AreEqual("Alice Smith", entity.FullName);
    // NOTE: Id=0 and Email="" are hardcoded — document or fix.
}
```

#### 5. `Validate_ValidInput_ReturnsSameInput` (line 64–69) — Self-referential, missing negative path

`ValidateEmail` returns the input when valid. The test asserts `input == result`, which is correct for this contract — but if the validation logic were removed entirely (`return input;` unconditionally), this test would still pass. There is **no test for invalid input**, so the `throw` path has zero coverage.

```csharp
// FIX — keep the happy-path test but add the critical negative case
[TestMethod]
public void ValidateEmail_ValidInput_ReturnsSameInput()
{
    var result = Validator.ValidateEmail("hello@world.com");
    Assert.AreEqual("hello@world.com", result);  // literal, not input variable
}

[TestMethod]
public void ValidateEmail_MissingAtSign_ThrowsArgumentException()
{
    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentException>(
        () => Validator.ValidateEmail("not-an-email"));
}
```

---

### 🟡 Medium — Maintainability

| # | Test | Issue | Fix |
